Eyewitnesses have said that "party thugs" associated with the Egyptian regime's Central Security Forces bearing government-issued weapons have been looting in Cairo.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} News from inside Alexandria as reported by an eye witness on [[Al-Arabiya]] news channel via phone, that a group of people captured a number of armed civilians trying to break into a local bank and after some investigation they learned that those armed civilians were actually part of the "Egyptian Undercover Police" with orders to create chaos.{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} Emad Gad, an analyst with the [[Al-Ahram Center for Political and Strategic Studies]], said that he has obtained information from a trustworthy source that "there have been orders from the very top to free known felons from the prisons, to arm them and to let them mingle with protesters."<ref name="Spiegel Anarchy">{{cite news|last1=Steinvorth|first1=Daniel|last2=Windfuhr|first=Volkhard|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|title="Mubarak will Ãgypten brennen sehen" ("Mubarak wants to see Egypt burn")|date=30 January 2011|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/0,1518,742498,00.html|accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref>
In [[Beni Suef]], south of Cairo, 17 protesters were shot dead by Egyptian police as they attempted to attack two police stations in the city. Eight more people were killed during protests in the city. In the Abu Zabaal prison in Cairo, eight people were killed as police clashed with inmates trying to escape. According to a Reuters tally, these deaths bring total death toll to at least 100; however, no figures could be accurately confirmed.<ref name="reuters2">{{cite news|title=Death toll in Egypt's protests tops 100 - sources|url=http://af.reuters.com/article/egyptNews/idAFLDE70S0LX20110129|accessdate=29 January 2011|work=[[Reuters]]|date=29 January 2011}}</ref>
